 for bestpractices and # Login / Signup

## Overview
Create a robust authentication entry experience for OfficeInventory AI that supports:
- Email/password login and signup
- Single Sign-On (SSO) readiness via SAML/OIDC
- “Request access” flow for new clients
- Clear error handling with user-friendly messages
- Redirect flows post-authentication (e.g., to dashboards or onboarding)
- Remember Me, password reset, and onboarding invitation handling
Ensure all front-end and back-end layers are secure, scalable, and compliant with enterprise requirements. Implement runtime safety as per project rules (null/undefined guards, proper defaults, and validated API responses).

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)
The Login / Signup page is the authentication entry point for users (internal teams, auditors, and invited external clients). Goals:
- Provide a frictionless entry path for existing users via email/password and SSO options
- Enable new client onboarding through a request access flow or invitation onboarding
- Offer an accessible password reset flow and a help/contact path for access issues
- Ensure consistent redirect behavior after successful authentication (e.g., to the audit dashboard, onboarding sequence, or organization/site picker)
- Expose a clear error surface with actionable guidance (invalid credentials, account locked, insufficient permissions, missing fields, SSO misconfigurations)

Connected features and context:
- Enterprise-grade authentication readiness (SSO, SAML/OIDC)
- Role-based access planning and future onboarding tasks
- Invitation-based onboarding for invited users
- Password reset and support channels
- The UI adheres to the project’s visual system and design guidelines (color palette, typography, spacing, and component styles)

UI elements and behavior:
- Email/Password form with:
  - Validation (required fields, email format, password strength hints)
  - Password visibility toggle
  - Remember Me checkbox
  - “Forgot Password” link
- Sign in with SSO area:
  - Buttons for SAML/OIDC identity providers (dynamic organization lookup or action)
  - Handling of errors from SSO flow (e.g., misconfigured provider, user not found)
- Signup invitation / request access:
  - If invited, display onboarding invitation context and continue button
  - If not invited, present “Request Access” CTA and a form (organization type, size, reason) if applicable
- Help CTA:
  - Contact support pathway with a modal or dedicated page
- Redirect logic:
  - Post-auth redirect to desired location (dashboard, onboarding stepper, or org/site picker)
  - Preserve return URL where appropriate
- Visual guidance:
  - Card-based layout with prominent form fields, action CTAs, and status indicators
  - Consistent top navigation and proper focus states for accessibility

---

## Components to Build
- AuthLayout
  - Wrapper for login/signup content with consistent header/footer, responsive behavior
- EmailPasswordSignInCard
  - Fields: email, password, Remember Me
  - Features: validation, show/hide password, inline error messaging
- SSOAuthCard
  - List of SSO providers (SAML/OIDC) with organization context support
  - Buttons that initiate redirection to IdP
  - Error handling for provider misconfigurations
- InvitationSignupCard
  - If user is invited: display invitation context, onboarding progress, and continue action
- RequestAccessCard
  - Form or CTA to initiate access request for new clients
  - Optional fields (organization name, role, justification) depending on requirements
- ForgotPasswordLink / PasswordResetModal
  - Trigger password reset workflow, validation of email, and success messaging
- HelpSupportCTA
  - Opens a contact/support flow (modal or route)
- RedirectHandler
  - Logic to determine and execute post-auth redirects
- Validation & Utilities
  - Input validators, error message mapper, and safe data adapters
- State & API Hooks
  - useAuth, useSSO, useInvitation, useAccessRequest, useNotification
  - Ensure all API results use data ?? [] and guard array methods with Array.isArray checks

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Tech stack assumptions: React 18+ with TypeScript, a component library consistent with the design system, and a state management approach suitable for auth flows (e.g., React Context or Redux Toolkit).
- Routing: Protected/redirect-capable routes; login path should redirect to a return URL when provided.
- Components must:
  - Use useState with appropriate defaults: useState<string>(""), useState<boolean>(false), useState<YourType[]>([]) where applicable
  - Guard all arrays with (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
  - Validate API responses: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Access nested API response safely with optional chaining
- UI/UX:
  - Email/Password form with accessible labels, aria-invalid, error messaging
  - Password field supports visibility toggle; show strength feedback if desired
  - Remember Me checkbox
  - SSO section with provider icons/text; click triggers IdP redirect with proper state preservation
  - Invitation flow rendered when an invitation payload exists; otherwise show Request Access CTA
  - Forgot Password flows to a reset route or modal
  - Keyboard accessible (tab order, Enter to submit)
- API integration placeholders:
  - Abstract API client interfaces for login, ssoInitiate, checkInvitation, requestAccess, passwordReset
  - All API calls should be simulated with clear expectations for real endpoints; ensure request payloads are well-formed
- Security:
  - Do not log sensitive data (passwords)
  - Use secure storage for tokens (redirect after login, but avoid exposing tokens in memory where unnecessary)
  - Implement CSRF/nonce protection patterns where applicable (depending on the framework)
- Error handling:
  - Distinguish client-side validation errors vs server-side/auth errors
  - Map error codes to user-friendly messages
  - Provide actionable guidance per error (e.g., "Incorrect password. Try again" vs "Account locked. Contact admin")

### Backend
- API Endpoints (mocked/defined):
  - POST /auth/login
    - Body: { email, password, rememberMe }
    - Response: { accessToken, refreshToken, user: { id, email, roles }, redirectTo }
  - GET /auth/sso/providers
    - Response: [{ id, name, type, authorizeUrl, clientId }]
  - POST /auth/sso/redirect
    - Body: { providerId, returnUrl, state }
    - Response: { redirectUrl }
  - POST /auth/invitations/validate
    - Body: { invitationId, email }
    - Response: { invited: boolean, invitationData }
  - POST /auth/invitations/accept
    - Body: { invitationId, userDetails }
    - Response: { accessToken, user }
  - POST /auth/request-access
    - Body: { organizationName, contactEmail, reason }
    - Response: { requestId, status }
  - POST /auth/password-reset
    - Body: { email }
    - Response: { message }
- Data Models (simplified for auth layer):
  - User: { id, email, name, roles, orgs }
  - Invitation: { id, email, organization, status, expiresAt }
  - AccessRequest: { id, organizationName, status, createdAt }
  - Session/Token: accessToken, refreshToken, exp
- Database considerations:
  - Ensure null-safe reads; use defaults when returning lists
  - Audit logs for login attempts, including outcomes (success/failure) and source (web/mobile)

### Integration
- Frontend ↔ Backend contract alignment:
  - Ensure API responses are validated: const payload = Array.isArray(res?.data) ? res.data : []
  - All endpoints return consistent shapes with safe defaults
  - Use a centralized error mapper to translate HTTP errors into UI messages
- SSO flow:
  - Frontend initiates SSO; backend returns a redirect URL or IdP metadata
  - After IdP completion, user is redirected back with a code/state; backend exchanges code for tokens
  - Frontend stores tokens securely and redirects to the landing page
- Invitation and onboarding:
  - If invitation present, frontend shows onboarding steps or continues to onboarding flow
  - Accept invitation posts to backend, which issues tokens and user session

---

## User Experience Flow
1. User lands on Login / Signup page
   - Sees Email/Password form, Remember Me, Forgot Password
   - Sees SSO options (SAML/OIDC) with organization context
   - Sees Signup Invitation / Request Access panel depending on invitation status
2. Email/Password path
   - User inputs email and password
   - Client-side validation runs (email format, required fields)
   - On submit, request to /auth/login; on success redirectTo target
   - On failure, display error with guidance (e.g., incorrect credentials, locked account, network issue)
3. SSO path
   - User clicks an SSO provider
   - Redirect to IdP; after authentication, IdP redirects back
   - Backend exchanges code for tokens; frontend stores tokens and redirects
4. Invitation path
   - If invited: show onboarding invite lane with continue button
   - On accept: backend creates user session and redirects to onboarding
5. Request Access path
   - User fills request form and submits
   - Backend processes and returns status; provide confirmation and next steps
6. Forgot Password
   - User clicks Forgot Password; enters email
   - Backend triggers reset; UI shows success message with next steps
7. Help / Support
   - Access point to contact support; may open a modal or navigate to a support page
8. Redirects
   - Post-auth, user lands on the intended page (dashboard or onboarding) and the app state reflects login

---

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models:
  - User: { id: string, email: string, name?: string, roles: string[], orgs?: string[] }
  - Invitation: { id: string, email: string, organization: string, status: string, expiresAt?: string }
  - AccessRequest: { id: string, organizationName: string, status: string, createdAt: string }
  - Session: { accessToken: string, refreshToken?: string, expiresAt: string }
- API Endpoints (as above) with versioned paths (e.g., /api/v1/auth/...)
- Security:
  - Use short-lived access tokens with refresh tokens
  - Enforce TLS, CSRF protections where applicable
  - Store tokens securely in httpOnly cookies or secure storage, avoid exposing tokens in UI
  - Validate inputs server-side; implement rate limiting and anomaly detection for login attempts
- Validation:
  - Client: email format, required fields, password length/strength hints
  - Server: sanitize inputs, ensure user exists, verify credentials, handle account status
- State Management:
  - Use React Context or a dedicated auth store
  - Ensure array-based data are initialized to [] and guarded when mapping
- Accessibility:
  - All interactive elements accessible via keyboard
  - ARIA roles and live regions for error/success messages

---

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Email/password login works with proper validation, error handling, and redirect
- [ ] SSO flow initiates correctly, handles IdP redirects, and finalizes authentication
- [ ] Invitation flow renders correctly when invitation data is present and onboarding proceeds
- [ ] Request Access path triggers backend process and returns a valid status
- [ ] Password reset flow completes and shows confirmation
- [ ] All API responses are validated; outputs sanitized with data ?? [] and Array.isArray guards where arrays are expected
- [ ] Frontend code initializes array-based state with correct defaults (useState<Type[]>([]))
- [ ] Error messaging is actionable and consistent across all authentication failure modes
- [ ] UI adheres to the provided visual style and design guidelines (colors, typography, spacing)

---

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
---
Visual Style

Color Palette:
- Primary background: Soft light gray (#F5F6F8)
- Card backgrounds: Slightly darker gray (#E8E9EC)
- Accent: Lime green (#C9FF52)
- Surfaces: White (#FFFFFF)
- Navigation/panels: Black (#18191A)
- Dividers/muted text: Mid-gray (#B6B7BA)
- Primary text: Dark gray (#232323)
- Secondary text: Gray (#6B6B6B)
- Supportive colors: Red (#FF5E5E), Orange (#FFC85E), Sky blue (#6ECFFF)

